Hypothesis Testing

We want to compare two categorical variables and the expected frequencies are all above five. A chi-squared test seems to be the most sensible solution here. We do not apply Yates continuity correction. We make us of the HolmBonferroni procedure for multi-test correction with a significance level of 0.05, i.e., alpha=0.05.

run_chi2 <- function(event_col, w, grps, conf_level, custom_levels){
  chi2_data <- dplyr::filter(data_clean, week==w & group %in% grps)
  # see https://stackoverflow.com/a/50126564 
  groups_conting <- table(factor(chi2_data$group, levels=grps), 
                          factor(chi2_data[[event_col]], levels=custom_levels))
  print(groups_conting)
  chi2_test <- chisq.test(groups_conting, correct=F)
  cat("\nTest: ", grps, w, "\n")
  cat(chisq_apa(chi2_test, format="text", print_n = TRUE))
  cat("\nP-Value:", chi2_test$p.value)
  if (event_col!="age"){
    cat("\nEffektstrke - Phi:", phi(groups_conting))
  }
  cat("\nCramer's V:", cramerV(groups_conting), "\n")
  return (chi2_test$p.value)
}

H1: Mails increase the activity of students.

For our analysis, we consider only one week at a time. By limiting the analysis to one week, we avoid issues with repeated measurements.

Personal/Specific E-Mails

In the first week, Group A receives the personal/specific intervention, whereas Group C has not received any intervention so far. With the chi-squared test, we want to find whether there is a relationship between the Group and the activity of the students. For the other personal/specific emails, we apply the same procedure.

p_val_ac_total_gr <- run_chi2("event_count_bool", 1, c("A", "C"), 0.95, c(TRUE, FALSE))
##    
##     TRUE FALSE

##   C   86     7

## chi^2(1, n = 193) = 0.02, p = .888
## P-Value: 0.8878639
## Effektstrke - Phi: 0.0101
## Cramer's V: 0.01015
p_val_bc_total_gr <- run_chi2("event_count_bool", 5, c("B", "C"), 0.95, c(TRUE, FALSE))
##    
##     TRUE FALSE
##   B   81     8
##   C   80    13
## 
## Test:  B C 5 
## chi^2(1, n = 182) = 1.11, p = .292
## P-Value: 0.2922317
## Effektstrke - Phi: 0.0781
## Cramer's V: 0.07807
p_val_ca_total_gr <- run_chi2("event_count_bool", 9, c("C", "A"), 0.95, c(TRUE, FALSE))
##    
##     TRUE FALSE
##   C   73    20
##   A   72    28
## 
## Test:  C A 9 
## chi^2(1, n = 193) = 1.09, p = .297
## P-Value: 0.2969648
## Effektstrke - Phi: 0.0751
## Cramer's V: 0.07507

Running the chi-squared test we get p-values of 0.8878639, 0.2922317 and 0.2969648. If we apply multi-test correction, we get p-values of 1 for all weeks. Hence, there is no significant effect of the mails.

H2: Mails increase the communication between students and tutors.

H3: Females are more active if contacted by a female tutor.

Here, we test whether females are more active if they are contacted by tutors of the same gender. For that, we determine the number of active days for each female student and compare the mean of two groups of female students, here contacted by a female tutor vs.contacted by a male tutor. We make use of the Welch t-test as this test is robust regarding its assumptions.

Female Students / Only direct communication

Here, we test whether females like to contact a female tutor more than a male tutor. That is, we consider bilateral communication.

data_female2 <- dplyr::filter(data_clean, gender=="f" & subgroup=="f" & week <= 12 & week > 0) %>% 
  group_by(pid) %>% summarise(sum_active_days = sum(bilateral_communication_active_days))

data_male2 <- dplyr::filter(data_clean, gender=="f" & subgroup=="m" & week <=12 & week > 0) %>% 
  group_by(pid) %>% summarise(sum_active_days = sum(bilateral_communication_active_days))

t_fm_direct <- t.test(data_female2$sum_active_days, data_male2$sum_active_days, 
                      alternative = "two.sided", var.equal = FALSE)

t_fm_direct
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  data_female2$sum_active_days and data_male2$sum_active_days

## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0

##  -3.1746093  0.6838857

cat("SD Tutor", sd(data_male2$sum_active_days))
## SD Tutor 6.226648

We get a p-value of 0.200382. With multi-test correction, this corresponds to 1, which is above our significance level. So there is no difference between those two groups.

Mutli-Test Correction

We make us of the HolmBonferroni procedure for multi-test correction.

options(scipen=3)
all_ps <- c(w1ps_all=p_val_ac_total_gr, w5ps_all=p_val_bc_total_gr, w9ps_all=p_val_ca_total_gr,
            w2us_all=p_val_bc_total_or, w4us_all=p_val_ab_total_or, w12us_all=p_val_ca_total_or,
            w1ps_mail=p_val_ac_mail_gr, w5ps_mail=p_val_bc_mail_gr, w9ps_mail=p_val_ca_mail_gr,
            w2us_mail=p_val_bc_mail_or, w4us_mail=p_val_ab_mail_or, w12us_mail=p_val_ca_mail_or, 
            t_test=t_fm_direct$p.value)
corrected_p <- p.adjust(all_ps, method = "holm")
corrected_p_df <- data.frame(p_value = all_ps, adjusted_p = corrected_p)
print(corrected_p_df)
